<taxonomicName id="4CFA4D52FFCEFFA0F6771949F5DEF28A" authorityName="Gervais" authorityYear="1850" box="[2452,2588,3406,3427]" class="Mammalia" family="Hyperoodontidae" genus="Mesoplodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cetacea" pageId="9" pageNumber="355" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Mesoplodon</taxonomicName>
traversil); 22. Gervais's Beaked Whale (
<taxonomicName id="4CFA4D52FFCEFFA0FDA11973FC87F264" authorityName="Gervais" authorityYear="1855" box="[578,837,3444,3469]" class="Mammalia" family="Hyperoodontidae" genus="Mesoplodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cetacea" pageId="9" pageNumber="355" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="europaeus">Mesoplodon europaeus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C3E0655AFFCDFFA3FF271512FDB6FDA0" pageId="10" pageNumber="356" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8B4536D1FFCDFFA3FF271512FDB6FDA0" blockId="10.[195,1400,277,630]" pageId="10" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis id="B98EEAC3FFCDFFA3FF271512FDE7FEDF" bold="true" box="[196,549,277,310]" pageId="10" pageNumber="356">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
As a new species, Deraniyagala’s Beaked Whale has not yet evaluated. However,it is mostlikely it will be listed on CITES Appendix II (along with most other beaked whales) and classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. There are no estimates of global population size of the Deraniyagala’s Beaked Whale. Like other species of beaked whales, the Deraniyagala’s Beaked Whale is potentially affected by ingestion of plastic debris and noise pollution, and individuals can be killed as bycatch in driftnet fisheries. Nevertheless, nothing is known about the form or extent of these potential impacts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
